        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We ask for observations of HCN(1-0) and HCO+(1-0) lines in two regions of the
nearby galaxy NGC3627.

From available single dish observations (Krips et al 2007) ratios of CO/HCN=0.1
and HCN/HCO+=1 can be used, assuming that this ratios are uniform over the whole
galaxy.

From our previous CO(1-0) observations obtained with IRAM PdBI at a resolution
of about 2 arcsec we estimate the sensitivity needed to detect the same
structures, observed in CO observations. The PdBI images sensitivity was ~ 6.5
mJy/beam in 10 km/s wide channels. In Krips (2007) the HCN line width reported
is 230 km/s, so a spectral resolution of 10 km/s will allow us to sample the
line appropriately. 
Correlator configuration: we centered the first baseband to observe  
the lines HCN(1-0) and HCO+(1-0), with a spectral sesolution of ~3 km/s,  
and we located the remaining three basebands,
covering the entire band, in order to estimate the continuum.
For these three baseband we used the FDM (1875 MHz bandwidth), with a spectral 
averaging to reduce the data rate.

The time on source estimated by the OT to achieve a sensitivity of 0.65 mJy in a
beam of 2 arcsec is almost 1 hr. If the HCN is distributed as the CO this
sensitivity will allow us to obtain at least a 5 sigma detection in each
channel.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
